          "cardUid": "Green",
          "title": "I am handsome",
          "content": "# I am handsome\n\nGreen's Theorem is a fundamental result in vector calculus that relates a line integral around a simple closed curve to a double integral over the plane region bounded by the curve. It states that for a positively oriented, piecewise smooth, simple closed curve \\(C\\) and a region \\(D\\) it encloses, if \\(P\\) and \\(Q\\) have continuous partial derivatives on an open region containing \\(D\\), then:\n\n\\[\n\\oint_C (P\\,dx + Q\\,dy) = \\iint_D \\left(\\frac{\\partial Q}{\\partial x} - \\frac{\\partial P}{\\partial y}\\right) dA\n\\]\n\nThis theorem is a special case of the more general Stokes' theorem and is widely used in physics and engineering, particularly in the study of fluid flow, electromagnetism, and the computation of area.\n\n<!-- BEGIN CRASHWEAVER: Green -->\n<!-- END CRASHWEAVER: Green -->\n\nBeyond its mathematical elegance, Green's Theorem illustrates the deep connection between local and global properties of functions, making it a cornerstone of multivariable calculus."
        },
        "rationale": "Creates a dedicated note for the focused card 'Green' with substantive markdown prose explaining Green's Theorem, satisfying the user's request."
      }
    ],
